ical and political perspective and from the Jewish and Israeli angle. To tell this story, Shai relies on rare documents, archival materials and interviews with individuals who were active in forming the relationship between these two states. He profiles Morris Cohen who, according to some, served as Sun Yat-sen’s personal advisor; gynecologist Dr. Ya’akov Rosenfeld, who rose to the rank of general in the Chinese Red Army and ended his career as a family physician in Tel Aviv; and international business magnate Shaul Eisenberg, otherwise known as “the king of China,” who executed the first Sino-Israeli military contacts. Shai also covers the attempts of major Israeli companies and business people to enter China, and describes the opportunities and risks involved when China purchases companies that are part of Israel’s national infrastructure.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aIsraeliszChina. 0aJewszChina. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / International Relations / Diplomacy.2bisacsh  aAsian studies.  aChina and Israel.  aChina and the Middle East.  aChina.  aChines-Jewish studies.  aChinese business.  aChinese companies.  aChinese investments abroad.  aChinese studies.  aInternational relations.  aIsrael.  aIsraeli Companies.  aIsraeli business.  aJewish studies.  aJewish-Chinese studies.  aJews and China.  aSino-Israeli relations.  aSino-Israeli.  abooks on global politics.  abooks on international business.  abooks on international relations.  abusiness.  adiplomacy.  aglobal diplomacy.  aglobal history.  ainternational business.  ainternational economy.  ainternational history.  ainternational politics.  apolitics.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAcademic Studies Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311068819108iTitle is part of eBook package:dD